Chapter 1 judge reaction templates — the feedback channel per PROPOSAL_player_driven_argument.md §4. Five templates correspond 1:1 to the judge_reaction_template field on each frame in argument_frames_ch1.json. The battle controller looks up the template by id when proposed_frame is committed at Phase 2 start (or earlier if the controller selects a Phase-2-skipping reaction such as icy_silence) and emits the judge_lines via Signals.dialogue_line_ready against the judge speaker. Patience drain happens in addition to the per-frame judicial_patience_delta_on_select declared in argument_frames_ch1.json — the deltas in this file are the in-round residual drain that occurs as the template's judge speech plays out.

Two-pass authoring per AGENTS.md §Casebook authoring. Code owns: id, follow_up_state_id, patience_drain_amount, post_reaction_player_options[].id, post_reaction_player_options[].leads_to_state_id, post_reaction_player_options[].judicial_patience_delta, post_reaction_player_options[].leads_to_round_outcome. Design owns: all judge_lines text, post_reaction_player_options[].text, in_fiction_notes.

Schema:
  templates: { <template_id>: {
    judge_lines (Design — Array of {speaker, text}; speaker is 'judge' or 'narrator' or one of the seated counsel for cross-talk; played in order),
    follow_up_state_id (Code — dialogue runner state id to resume after this template completes; typically a court_round state),
    patience_drain_amount (Code — int; subtracted from chapter1.judicial_patience after lines play; complements the per-frame delta),
    post_reaction_player_options (Code+Design — Array of options the player chooses after the judge reaction; each: {id, text, leads_to_state_id, judicial_patience_delta, leads_to_round_outcome}),
    in_fiction_notes (Design — meta notes for the human reviewer; not loaded at runtime)
  } }
